The problem is that when you walk into a small shop, you look around, you look at what\'s there, you say goodbye, and the shopkeeper thinks \"oh my God, these people are trampling on my dreams\". And next time he\'ll try to grab the customer and hand him anything.

The problem is the principle of trade. Why buy, why sell? This logic is based on the ownership of goods, on the freedom of contract, and the use of a symbolic value called money. The aim of this game is that for any object you must have the corresponding symbolic value in your pocket.

In this framework, if access to goods is a right, money is the condition for access to this right. So money is superior to the right. In practice this means that money gives all rights. Similarly, a crime to capture money is rewarded by all the sellers in the world. 

Finally, a right without money is a right that is denied, like the right to food. Money is the right. We talk about capitalism, but in fact we are talking about the right of access to goods, and ultimately about \"what justifies\" the distribution of vital goods and commodities.

The principle of trade is to capture value along a supply chain that is far greater than the need, since the need is incalculable. That is, knowing that it is impossible to estimate the value of work in terms of money.

The buyers of a single tomato must also pay for a whole system of debt-technology-insurance-marketing etc. The yoaths of the rich must also be financed. And their pool on the yoath. And the hoard board on the pool on the yoath. But other than that, tomatoes are free, like everything else that grows on trees.

If there are rich people with millions of years of wages in their tight pockets, it\'s because society accepts it. People are willing to give them anything they want in exchange for a bit of that symbolic currency that is supposed to justify why I can buy food.

That\'s why we need to go back to basics, rather than using words whose meaning can be emptied. In what way and on what scale is it reasonable to speak of \"property\", on which \"an exchange\" is based, against a currency that is supposed to signify \"value\"? The basic question is: \"What makes things valuable? 

And the systemic question, which should be of interest to many people now that we have entered the computer age, is \"how do we make a system that works?\"


